 "components": {
  "instruction": "Classify the given text into one of these categories: alarm_query, alarm_set, calendar_query, calendar_remove, calendar_set, cooking_recipe, datetime_query, email_query, email_sendemail, general_quirky, iot_hue_lightoff, lists_createoradd, lists_query, lists_remove, music_query, news_query, play_audiobook, play_music, play_podcasts, play_radio, qa_currency, qa_definition, qa_factoid, qa_stock, recommendation_events, recommendation_locations, social_post, takeaway_order, transport_query, weather_query.\n\nImportant classification rules:\n\n1. **Calendar vs Lists vs Alarms:**\n   - 'calendar_set' is for setting up meetings, appointments, reminders, or events that are scheduled for specific dates or times (e.g., \"for the twentieth october meeting\", \"for my five p. m. meeting\")\n   - 'alarm_set' is for setting alarms or wake-up calls without specific meeting/event context\n   - 'lists_createoradd' is for creating general lists (e.g., shopping lists, to-do lists) that are not tied to specific calendar events or meetings\n   - The key differentiator is the presence of a scheduled event/meeting context combined with a specific date/time\n\n2. **Weather-related queries:**\n   - Any request involving temperature, weather conditions, or weather-based notifications should be classified as 'weather_query', NOT 'alarm_query' or 'alarm_set'\n   - This includes conditional alerts based on weather metrics (e.g., \"alert me when the outside temperature reaches sixty eight degrees\")\n   - Even if the text uses words like \"alert\" or \"notify\", if the core intent is about weather conditions or temperature, classify it as 'weather_query'\n\n3. **Query vs Set vs Remove:**\n   - Use '_query' categories when asking about existing information\n   - Use '_set' categories when creating or scheduling new items\n   - Use '_remove' categories when deleting or canceling items\n\n4. **General Strategy:**\n   - Identify the primary domain or subject matter of the request (weather, calendar, music, etc.)\n   - Then determine the action type (query, set, remove, etc.)\n   - Pay special attention to the main intent rather than being misled by action words like \"alert\" or \"remind\" that might appear in various contexts"
 },
